{{good article}} {{short description|ancient Mesopotamian god}} {{Distinguish|Dumuzid the Fisherman}} {{redirect|Tammuz|the Babylonian month named after him|Tammuz (Babylonian calendar)|the corresponding Hebrew month|Tammuz (Hebrew month)}} {{Infobox deity | type = Mesopotamian | name = Dumuzid | image = Marriage of Inanna and Dumuzi.png | alt = | caption = Ancient Sumerian depiction of the marriage of [[Inanna]] and Dumuzid{{sfn|Lung|2014}} | god_of = God of shepherds | abode = [[Heaven]] (for half the year) [[Kur]] (for the other half) | symbol = | consort = [[Inanna]] (later known as Ishtar) | parents = [[Sirtur]] and an unknown father | siblings = [[Geshtinanna]] (sister), Amashilama (not usually, but in some texts said to be his sister) | children = | planet = | mount = | Greek_equivalent = [[Adonis]] | equivalent1_type = East Semitic | equivalent1 = Tammuz | equivalent2_type = Levantine | equivalent2 = Tammuz/Adonis }}
'''Dumuzid''',{{efn|cuneiform:{{Script/Cuneiform|𒌉𒍣𒉺𒇻}}; [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]]: ''Dumuzid sipad'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=c.2.1.1&display=Crit&charenc=gcirc&lineid=c211.15#c211.15|title=The Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|website=etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref> derived from the Sumerian words meaning "faithful son".{{sfn|Mitchell|2005|page=169}}}} later known by the alternate form '''Tammuz''',{{efn|{{lang-syr|ܬܡܘܙ}}; {{lang-he-n|תַּמּוּז}}, [[Transliterated]] [[Hebrew]]: ''{{transl|he|Tammuz}}'', [[Tiberian Hebrew]]: ''{{transl|he|Tammûz}}''; {{lang-ar|تمّوز}} ''{{transl|ar|ALA|Tammūz}}''; {{lang-akk|Duʾzu}}, ''{{lang|akk|Dūzu}}''}} is an [[List of Mesopotamian deities|ancient Mesopotamian god]] associated with shepherds, who was also the primary consort of the goddess [[Inanna]] (later known as Ishtar). In Sumerian mythology, Dumuzid's sister was [[Geshtinanna]], the goddess of vegetation. In the [[Sumerian King List]], Dumuzid is listed as an [[antediluvian]] king of the city of [[Bad-tibira]] and also an early king of the city of [[Uruk]]. In the Sumerian poem ''Inanna Prefers the Farmer'', Dumuzid competes against the farmer [[Enkimdu]] for Inanna's hand in marriage. In ''[[Inanna#Descent into the Underworld|Inanna's Descent into the Underworld]]'', Dumuzid fails to mourn Inanna's death and, when she returns from the [[Ancient Mesopotamian Underworld|Underworld]], she allows the ''[[gallu|galla]]'' demons to drag him down to the Underworld as her replacement. Inanna later regrets this decision and decrees that Dumuzid will spend half the year in the Underworld, but the other half of the year with her, while his sister Geshtinanna stays in the Underworld in his place, thus resulting in the cycle of the seasons.
[[Gilgamesh]] references Tammuz in Tablet VI of the ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]'' as one of Ishtar's past lovers, who was turned into an [[Roller|''allalu'' bird]] with a broken wing. Dumuzid was associated with fertility and vegetation and the hot, dry summers of Mesopotamia were believed to be caused by Dumuzid's yearly death. During the [[Tammuz (Babylonian calendar)|month in midsummer bearing his name]], people all across Mesopotamia would engage in public, ritual mourning for him. During the late twentieth century, scholars widely thought that, during the Sumerian [[Akitu]] festival, kings may have established their legitimacy by taking on the role of Dumuzid and engaging in ritualized sexual intercourse with the high priestess of Inanna as part of a [[Hieros gamos|sacred marriage]] ceremony. This notion is now generally rejected by scholars as a misinterpretation of Sumerian literary texts. The cult of Dumuzid was later spread to the Levant and to Greece, where he became known under the [[West Semitic languages|West Semitic]] name [[Adonis]].
The cult of Ishtar and Tammuz continued to thrive until the eleventh century AD and survived in parts of Mesopotamia as late as the eighteenth century. Tammuz is mentioned by name in the [[Book of Ezekiel]] and possibly alluded to in other passages from the [[Hebrew Bible]]. In late nineteenth and early twentieth century [[Religious studies|scholarship of religion]], Tammuz was widely seen as a prime example of the [[archetype|archetypal]] [[Dying-and-rising deity|dying-and-rising god]], but the discovery of the full Sumerian text of ''Inanna's Descent'' in the mid-twentieth century disproved the previous scholarly assumption that the narrative ended with Dumuzid's resurrection and instead revealed that it ended with Dumuzid's death. The existence of the "dying-and-rising god" archetype has been largely rejected by modern scholars.
==Worship== [[File:Mythe du dieu dumuzi.jpg|thumb|right|Ancient Mesopotamian clay tablet dating to the [[Amorites|Amorite Period]] (c. 2000-1600 BC), containing a lamentation over the death of Dumuzid, currently held in the [[Louvre Museum]] in Paris]]
The Assyriologists [[Jeremy Black (assyriologist)|Jeremy Black]] and Anthony Green describe the early history of Dumuzid's cult as "complex and bewildering".{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=72}} According to the [[Sumerian King List]] ([[Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|ETCSL]] [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section2/tr211.htm 2.1.1]), Dumuzid was the fifth [[antediluvian]] king of the city of [[Bad-tibira]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=72}} Dumuzid was also listed as an early king of [[Uruk]],{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=72}} where he was said to have come from the nearby village of [[Kuara (Sumer)|Kuara]]{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=72}} and to have been the consort of the goddess Inanna.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=72}} As ''Dumuzid sipad'' ("Dumuzid the Shepherd"), Dumuzid was believed to be the provider of [[milk]],{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|page=74}} which was a rare, seasonal commodity in ancient Sumer due to the fact that it could not easily be stored without [[Food spoilage|spoiling]].{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|page=84}}
In addition to being the god of shepherds, Dumuzid was also an agricultural deity associated with the growth of plants.{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|page=116}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|pages=87–88}} Ancient Near Eastern peoples associated Dumuzid with the springtime, when the land was fertile and abundant,{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|page=116}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|pages=83–84}} but, during the summer months, when the land was dry and barren, it was thought that Dumuzid had "died".{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|page=116}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|pages=83–87}} During the month of Dumuzid, which fell in the middle of summer, people all across Sumer would mourn over his death.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=73}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|pages=74–84}} This seems to have been the primary aspect of his cult.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=73}} In Lagash, the month of Dumuzid was the sixth month of the year.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=73}} This month and the holiday associated with it was later transmitted from the Sumerians to Babylonians and other [[East Semitic]] peoples,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=73}} with its name transcribed into those languages as ''Tammuz''.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=73}} A ritual associated with the [[Ekur]] temple in [[Nippur]] equates Dumuzid with the snake-god [[Ištaran]], who in that ritual, is described as having died.{{sfn|Simons|2017|page=86}}
Dumuzid was also identified with the god Ama-ušumgal-ana,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=72}} who was originally a local god worshipped in the city of [[Lagash]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|pages=72–73}} In some texts, Ama-ušumgal-ana is described as a heroic warrior.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=73}} As Ama-ušumgal-ana, Dumuzid is associated with the [[date palm]] and its fruits.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|pages=73–74}} This aspect of Dumuzid's cult was always joyful in character{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|page=74}} and had no associations with the darker stories involving his death.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|page=74}} To ancient Mesopotamian peoples, the date palm represented stability,{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|page=74}} because it was one of the few crops that could be harvested all year, even during the dry season.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|page=74}} In some Sumerian poems, Dumuzid is referred to as "my Damu", which means "my son".{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|pages=57, 73}}{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|pages=73, 89}} This name is usually applied to him in his role as the personification of the power that causes the sap to rise in trees and plants.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|page=73}} Damu is the name most closely associated with Dumuzid's return in autumn after the dry season has ended.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|page=89}} This aspect of his cult emphasized the fear and exhaustion of the community after surviving the devastating summer.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|page=89}}
Dumuzid had virtually no power outside of his distinct realm of responsibilities.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|pages=74–76}} Very few prayers addressed to him are extant{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|pages=75–76}} and, of those that are, almost all of them are simply requests for him to provide more milk, more grain, more cattle, etc.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|pages=75–76}} The sole exception to this rule is a single Assyrian inscription in which a man requests Tammuz that, when he descends to the Underworld, he should take with him a troublesome ghost who has been haunting him.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2008|page=76}} The cult of Tammuz was particularly associated with women, who were the ones responsible for mourning his death.{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|page=116}} The custom of planting miniature gardens with fast-growing plants such as [[lettuce]] and [[fennel]], which would then be placed out in the hot sun to sprout before withering in the heat, was a well-attested custom in ancient Greece associated with the festival of [[Adonia]] in honor of [[Adonis]], the Greek version of Tammuz;{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}}{{sfn|Detienne|1977}}{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|Willem|1999|page=9}} some scholars have argued based on references in the [[Hebrew Bible]] that this custom may have been a continuation of an earlier oriental practice.{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|Willem|1999|page=9}} The same women who mourned the death of Tammuz also prepared cakes for his consort Ishtar, the Queen of Heaven.{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|pages=115–117}} These cakes would be baked in ashes{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|pages=115–117}} and several clay cake molds discovered at [[Mari, Syria]] reveal that they were also at least sometimes shaped like naked women.{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|pages=115–117}}
According to the early scholar [[Samuel Noah Kramer]], towards the end of the third millennium BC, kings of Uruk may have established their legitimacy by taking on the role of Dumuzid as part of a "[[hieros gamos|sacred marriage]]" ceremony.{{sfn|Kramer|1970|page=}} This ritual lasted for one night on the tenth day of the [[Akitu]],{{sfn|Kramer|1970|page=}}{{sfn|Nemet-Nejat|1998|page=196}} the Sumerian new year festival,{{sfn|Nemet-Nejat|1998|page=196}} which was celebrated annually at the [[spring equinox]].{{sfn|Kramer|1970|page=}} As part of the ritual, it was thought that the king would engage in ritualized sexual intercourse with the high priestess of Inanna, who took on the role of the goddess.{{sfn|Kramer|1970|page=}}{{sfn|Nemet-Nejat|1998|page=196}} In the late twentieth century, the historicity of the sacred marriage ritual was treated by scholars as more-or-less an established fact,{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=128}} but, in the early 2000s, largely due to the writings of Pirjo Lapinkivi, many scholars began to reject the notion of an actual sex ritual, instead seeing "sacred marriage" as a symbolic rather than a physical union.{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=128}}
==Mythology== ===Sumerian=== ====Marriage to Inanna==== [[File:Inanna prefers the farmer. Enkimdu and Damuzi were mentioned. Terracotta tablet from Nippur, Iraq. 1st half of the 2nd millennium BCE. Ancient Orient Museum, Istanbul.jpg|thumb|Original Sumerian tablet of the ''Courtship of Inanna and Dumuzid'']]
The poem ''Inanna Prefers the Farmer'' (ETCSL [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section4/tr40833.htm 4.0.8.3.3]) begins with a rather playful conversation between Inanna and her brother [[Utu]], who incrementally reveals to her that it is time for her to marry.{{sfn|Kramer|1961|page=101}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=30–49}} Dumuzid comes to court her, along with a farmer named [[Enkimdu]].{{sfn|Kramer|1961|page=101}} At first, Inanna prefers the farmer,{{sfn|Kramer|1961|page=101}} but Utu and Dumuzid gradually persuade her that Dumuzid is the better choice for a husband, arguing that, for every gift the farmer can give to her, the shepherd can give her something even better.{{sfn|Kramer|1961|pages=102–103}} In the end, Inanna marries Dumuzid.{{sfn|Kramer|1961|pages=102–103}} The shepherd and the farmer reconcile their differences, offering each other gifts.{{snf|Kramer|1961|pages=101–103}} Samuel Noah Kramer compares the myth to the Biblical story of [[Cain and Abel]] because both myths center around a farmer and a shepherd competing for divine favor and, in both stories, the deity in question ultimately chooses the shepherd.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=101}}
A vast number of erotic love poems celebrating the consummation of Inanna and Dumuzid have survived.{{sfn|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=150–155}}{{sfn|Leick|2013|pages=64–79, 90–96}} Two excerpts from a representative example are translated below:
[[File:Samuel and Saidye Bronfman Archaeology WingDSCN4978.JPG|thumb|upright=1.3|Erotic [[terracotta]] votive plaque dating to the [[First Babylonian Dynasty|Old Babylonian Period]] ({{circa}} 1830 BC — c. 1531). Representations of this type were once interpreted as evidence for a "sacred marriage" ritual in which the king would take on the role of Dumuzid and engage in sexual intercourse with the priestess of Inanna.{{sfn|Kramer|1970|page=}}{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|pages=157–158}}{{sfn|Nemet-Nejat|1998|page=196}}{{sfn|Pryke|2017|pages=127–128}} This interpretation is now generally seen as a misinterpretation of Sumerian literary texts.{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=128}}]]
{| class="wikitable" |- |'''Transliterated Sumerian text''' (ETCSL [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.4.08.16# 4.08.16])||'''English translation by Samuel Noah Kramer and Diane Wolkstein''' |- |<poem lang="gmh" style="font-style:italic;"> gal<sub>4</sub>-la jar-ra<sup>?</sup> ne-en GAG X [...] si-gin<sub>7</sub> <sup>jic</sup>mar gal-e /kece<sub>2</sub>\ [...] ma<sub>2</sub> an-na ne-en ec<sub>2</sub> la<sub>2</sub> [...] ud-sakar gibil-gin<sub>7</sub> hi-li /gur3\-[ru-ju<sub>10</sub>] kislah ne-en edin-na cub<sup>?</sup>-[...] a-cag<sub>4</sub>? uz<sup>mucen</sup> ne-en uz<sup>mucen</sup> dur<sub>2</sub>-[ra]-/ju<sub>10</sub>\ a-cag<sub>4</sub> an-na ne-en a ma-ra-ju<sub>10</sub> ma-a gal<sub>4</sub>-la-ju<sub>10</sub> du<sub>6</sub> du<sub>8</sub>-du<sub>8</sub>-a a ma-«a»-ra ki-sikil-jen a-ba-a ur<sub>11</sub>-ru-a-bi gal<sub>4</sub>-la-ju<sub>10</sub> ki duru<sub>5</sub> a ma-ra ga-ca-an-jen gud a-ba-a bi<sub>2</sub>-ib<sub>2</sub>-gub-be<sub>2</sub> ... ga sig<sub>7</sub>-a-ma-ab mu-ud-na-ju<sub>10</sub> ga sig<sub>7</sub>-/a\-[ma-ab] mu-ud-na-ju<sub>10</sub> me-e ga de<sub>3</sub>-e-da-/na<sub>8</sub>\-[na<sub>8</sub>] am <sup>d</sup>dumu-zid ga sig<sub>7</sub>-a-ma-/ab\ mu-ud-na-ju<sub>10</sub> me-e ga de<sub>3</sub>-/e-da\-[na<sub>8</sub>-na<sub>8</sub>] ga ud<sub>5</sub>-da-ke<sub>4</sub> amac [...] nin car<sub>2</sub>-ra dugcakir kug-ja<sub>2</sub> sug<sub>4</sub>-[...] <sup>d</sup>dumu-zid ga am-si-har-ra-/an\-[na ...] </poem> |<poem lang="gmh" style="font-style:italic;"> My vulva, the horn, The Boat of Heaven, Is full of eagerness like the young moon. My untilled land lies fallow. As for me, Inanna, Who will plow my vulva? Who will plow my high field? Who will plow my wet ground? As for me, the young woman, Who will plow my vulva? Who will station the ox there? Who will plow my vulva?{{sfn|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|page=37}} ... Make your milk sweet and thick, my bridegroom. My shepherd, I will drink your fresh milk. Wild bull, Dumuzi, make your milk sweet and thick. I will drink your fresh milk. Let the milk of the goat flow in my sheepfold. Fill my holy churn with honey cheese. Lord Dumuzi, I will drink your fresh milk.{{sfn|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|page=39}} </poem> |}
====Death==== =====Main narrative===== [[File:Dumuzi aux enfers.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Ancient Sumerian [[cylinder seal]] impression showing Dumuzid being tortured in the Underworld by the ''[[gallu|galla]]'' demons]]
Towards the end of the epic poem ''[[Inanna#Descent into the Underworld|Inanna's Descent into the Underworld]]'' (ETCSL [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section1/tr141.htm 1.4.1]), Dumuzid's wife Inanna escapes from the Underworld,{{snf|Kramer|1961|pages=94–95}} but is pursued by a horde of ''[[Gallu|galla]]'' demons, who insist that someone else must take her place in the Underworld.{{snf|Kramer|1961|pages=94–95}} They first come upon Inanna's ''sukkal'' Ninshubur and attempt to take her,{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=95}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=68–69}} but Inanna stops them, insisting that Ninshubur is her loyal servant and that she had rightfully mourned for her while she was in the Underworld.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=95}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=68–69}} They next come upon Shara, Inanna's beautician, who is still in mourning.{{snf|Kramer|1961|pages=95–96}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=69–70}} The demons attempt to take him, but Inanna insists that they may not, because he had also mourned for her.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=96}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=70}} The third person they come upon is Lulal, who is also in mourning.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=96}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=70–71}} The demons try to take him, but Inanna stops them once again.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=96}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=70–71}} Finally, they come upon Dumuzid, who is lavishly clothed and resting beneath a tree, or sitting on Inanna's throne, entertained by slave-girls.{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|page=71}} Inanna, displeased, decrees that the demons shall take him, using language which echoes the speech Ereshkigal gave while condemning her.{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|page=71}} The demons then drag Dumuzid down to the Underworld.{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|page=71}}
The Sumerian poem ''The Dream of Dumuzid'' (ETCSL [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section1/tr143.htm 1.4.3]) begins with Dumuzid telling Geshtinanna about a frightening dream he has experienced.{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=74–78}}{{efn|''Dumuzid's Dream'' is attested in seventy-five known sources, fifty-five of which come from [[Nippur]], nine from [[Ur]], three probably from the region around [[Sippar]], one each from [[Uruk]], [[Kish (Sumer)|Kish]], [[Shaduppum]], and [[Susa]].{{sfn|Tinney|2018|page=86}}}} Then the ''galla'' demons arrive to drag Dumuzid down into the Underworld as Inanna's replacement. Dumuzid flees and hides. The ''galla'' demons brutally torture Geshtinanna in an attempt to force her to tell them where Dumuzid is hiding. Geshtinanna, however, refuses to tell them where her brother has gone. The ''galla'' go to Dumuzid's unnamed "friend", who betrays Dumuzid, telling the ''galla'' exactly where Dumuzid is hiding. The ''galla'' capture Dumuzid, but [[Utu]], the god of the Sun, who is also Inanna's brother, rescues Dumuzid by transforming him into a [[gazelle]].{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=74–84}} Eventually, the ''galla'' recapture Dumuzid and drag him down into the Underworld.{{sfn|Tinney|2018|page=86}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=83–84}}
[[File:Dieu mort.jpg|thumb|Terracotta plague dating to the [[Amorites|Amorite Period]] ({{circa}} 2000-1600 BC) showing a dead god (probably Dumuzid) resting in his coffin]]
In the Sumerian poem ''The Return of Dumuzid'', which begins where ''The Dream of Dumuzid'' ends, Geshtinanna laments continually for days and nights over Dumuzid's death, joined by Inanna, who has apparently experienced a change of heart, and [[Sirtir|Sirtur]], Dumuzid's mother.{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=85–87}} The three goddesses mourn continually until a [[fly]] reveals to Inanna the location of her husband.{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=87–89}} Together, Inanna and Geshtinanna go to the place where the fly has told them they will find Dumuzid.{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=88–89}} They find him there and Inanna decrees that, from that point onwards, Dumuzid will spend half of the year with her sister [[Ereshkigal]] in the Underworld and the other half of the year in Heaven with her, while Geshtinanna takes his place in the Underworld.{{snf|Kramer|1966|page=31}}{{sfn|Penglase|1994|page=18}}{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|pages=85–89}}
=====Other versions===== Other texts describe different and contradictory accounts of Dumuzid's death.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|pages=77–78}} The text of the poem ''Inanna and Bilulu'' (ETCSL [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section1/tr144.htm 1.4.4]), discovered at Nippur, is badly mutilated{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}} and scholars have interpreted it in a number of different ways.{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}} The beginning of the poem is mostly destroyed,{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}} but seems to be a lament.{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}} The intelligible part of the poem describes Inanna pining after her husband Dumuzid, who is in the steppe watching his flocks.{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}} Inanna sets out to find him.{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}} After this, a large portion of the text is missing.{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}} When the story resumes, Inanna is being told that Dumuzid has been murdered.{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}} Inanna discovers that the old bandit woman Bilulu and her son Girgire are responsible.{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=166}} She travels along the road to Edenlila and stops at an [[inn]], where she finds the two murderers.{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}} Inanna stands on top of a stool{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}} and transforms Bilulu into "the waterskin that men carry in the desert",{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}}{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=109}}{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=166}} forcing her to pour the funerary [[libation]]s for Dumuzid.{{sfn|Leick|1998|page=89}}
''Dumuzid and Geshtinanna'' begins with demons encouraging Inanna to conquer the Underworld.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=77}} Instead, she hands Dumuzid over to them.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=77}} They put Dumuzid's feet, hands, and neck in the [[stocks]]{{sfn|Shushan|2009|pages=77–78}} and torture him using hot pokers.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} They strip him naked, do "evil" to him, and [[Sensory deprivation|cover his face with his own garment]].{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} Finally, Dumuzid prays to Utu for help.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} Utu transforms Dumuzid into a creature that is part eagle and part snake, allowing him to escape back to Geshtinanna.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} In the text known as ''The Most Bitter Cry'', Dumuzid is chased by the "seven evil deputies of the netherworld"{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} and, as he is running, he falls into a river.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} Near an apple tree on the other bank, he is dragged into the Underworld,{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} where everything simultaneously "exists" and "does not exist", perhaps indicating that they exist in insubstantial or immaterial forms.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}}
[[File:Le dieu de l ete et dumuzi.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Akkadian cylinder seal impression from [[Girsu]] ({{circa}} 2340 - 2150 BC) showing a mythological scene.{{sfn|Kramer|1961|pages=32–33}} The figure in the center appears to be a god, perhaps Gilgamesh, who is bending the trunk of a tree into a curve as he chops it down.{{sfn|Kramer|1961|pages=32–33}} Underneath the tree, a god ascending from the Underworld, possibly Dumuzid, hands a mace-like object to a goddess,{{sfn|Kramer|1961|pages=32–33}} possibly Inanna or one of Dumuzid's female relatives.]]
A collection of lamentations for Dumuzid entitled ''In the Desert by the Early Grass'' describes Damu, the "dead anointed one", being dragged down to the Underworld by demons,{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} who blindfold him, tie him up, and [[Sleep deprivation|forbid him from sleeping]].{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} Damu's mother tries to follow him into the Underworld,{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} but Damu is now a disembodied spirit, "lying in" the winds, "in the lightnings and in tornadoes".{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} Damu's mother is also unable to eat the food or drink the water in the Underworld, because it is "bad".{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} Damu travels along the road of the Underworld and encounters various spirits.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} He meets the ghost of a small child, who tells him that it is lost;{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=78}} the ghost of a singer agrees to accompany the child.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|pages=78–79}} Damu asks the spirits to send a message to his mother, but they cannot because they are dead and the living cannot hear the dead's voices.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=79}} Damu, however, manages to tell his mother to dig up his blood and chop it into pieces.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=79}} Damu's mother gives the congealed blood to Damu's sister Amashilama, who is a leech.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=79}} Amashilama mixes the congealed blood into a brew of beer, which Damu must drink in order to be restored to life.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=79}} Damu, however, realizes that he is dead and declares that he is not in the "grass which shall grow for his mother again", nor in the "waters which will rise".{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=79}} Damu's mother blesses him{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=79}} and Amashilama dies to join him in the Underworld.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=79}} She tells him that "the day that dawns for you will also dawn for me; the day you see, I shall also see",{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=79}} referring to the fact that day in the world above is night in the Underworld.{{sfn|Shushan|2009|page=79}}
===Akkadian=== [[File:European roller.jpg|thumb|In the Akkadian ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]'', Tammuz is described as a "colorful ''allalu'' bird",{{sfn|Dalley|1989|page=78}} possibly a [[European roller]].{{sfn|Dalley|1989|pages=129, n. 56}}{{sfn|Sandars|1972|page=86}}]]
In the myth of Adapa, Dumuzid and [[Ningishzida]] are the two doorkeepers of [[Anu]], the god of the heavens,{{sfn|McCall|1990|page=66}}{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=72}}{{sfn|Dalley|1989|page=187}} who speak out in favor of [[Adapa]], the priest of [[Enki|Ea]], as he stands trial before Anu.{{sfn|McCall|1990|page=66}}{{sfn|Dalley|1989|page=187}} In Tablet VI of the standard [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]'', Ishtar (Inanna) attempts to seduce the hero [[Gilgamesh]],{{sfn|Dalley|1989|pages=129, n. 56}}{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=146}} but he rebuffs her, reminding her that she had struck Tammuz (Dumuzid), "the lover of [her] youth", decreeing that he should "keep weeping year after year".{{sfn|Dalley|1989|pages=129, n. 56}}{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=146}} Gilgamesh describes Tammuz as a colorful ''allalu'' bird (possibly a [[European roller|European]] or [[Indian roller]]),{{sfn|Dalley|1989|pages=129, n. 56}}{{sfn|Sandars|1972|page=86}} whose wing has been broken and now spends all his time "in the woods crying 'My wing!'" (Tablet VI, section ii, lines 11-15).{{sfn|Dalley|1989|pages=78–79}} Gilgamesh may be referring to an alternative account of Dumuzid's death, different from the ones recorded in extant texts.{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=146}}
Anton Moortgat has interpreted Dumuzid as the antithesis of Gilgamesh:{{sfn|Ataç|2018|page=10}} Gilgamesh refuses Ishtar's demand for him to become her lover, seeks immortality, and fails to find it;{{sfn|Ataç|2018|page=10}} Dumuzid, by contrast, accepts Ishtar's offer and, as a result of her love, is able to spend half the year in Heaven, even though he is condemned to the Underworld for the other half.{{sfn|Ataç|2018|page=10}} Mehmet-Ali Ataç further argues that the "Tammuz model" of immortality was far more prevalent in the ancient Near East than the "Gilgamesh model".{{sfn|Ataç|2018|page=10}} In a chart of antediluvian generations in Babylonian and Biblical traditions, [[William Wolfgang Hallo]] associates Dumuzid with the composite half-man, half-fish counselor or culture hero ([[Apkallu]]) An-Enlilda, and suggests an equivalence between Dumuzid and [[Enoch (ancestor of Noah)|Enoch]] in the [[Seth]]ite Genealogy given in [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] chapter 5.<ref>Hallo, William W. and William Kelly Simpson, ''The Ancient Near East: A History'', Harcourt Brace Jovanovich, Inc., New York, 1971, p. 32</ref>
==Later worship== ===In the Bible=== [[File:126.The Prophet Ezekiel.jpg|thumb|In {{bibleverse|Ezekiel|8:14|9}}, the prophet [[Ezekiel]], shown here in this illustration from 1866 by [[Gustave Doré]], witnesses women mourning the death of Tammuz outside the [[Second Temple]].{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=195}}{{sfn|Warner|2016|page=211}}{{sfn|Middlemas|2005|pages=114–115}}]]
The cult of Ishtar and Tammuz may have been introduced to the [[Kingdom of Judah]] during the reign of [[Manasseh of Judah|King Manasseh]]{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=193}} and the [[Old Testament]] contains numerous allusions to them.{{sfn|Pryke|2017|pages=193–195}} {{bibleverse|Ezekiel|8:14|9}} mentions Tammuz by name:{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=195}}{{sfn|Warner|2016|page=211}}{{sfn|Middlemas|2005|pages=114–115}} "Then he brought me to the door of the gate of the Lord's house which was toward the north; and, behold, there sat women weeping for Tammuz. Then said he unto to me, 'Hast thou seen this, O son of man? turn thee yet again, and thou shalt see greater abominations than these."{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=195}}
Ezekiel's testimony is the only direct mention of Tammuz in the [[Hebrew Bible]],{{sfn|Smith|2002|page=182}}{{sfn|Middlemas|2005|page=115}} but the cult of Tammuz may also be alluded to in {{bibleverse|Isaiah|17:10–11|9}}:{{sfn|Smith|2002|page=182}}{{sfn|Middlemas|2005|page=115}}<blockquote>"Because thou hast forgotten the God of thy salvation, and hast not been mindful of the rock of thy strength, therefore shalt thou plant pleasant plants, and shalt set it with strange slips: In the day shalt thou make thy plant to grow, and in the morning shalt thou make thy seed to flourish: but the harvest shall be a heap in the day of grief and of desperate sorrow."</blockquote> This passage may be describing the miniature gardens that women would plant in honor of Tammuz during his festival.{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|Willem|1999|page=9}} {{bibleverse|Isaiah|1:29–30|9}}, {{bibleverse|Isaiah|65:3|9}}, and {{bibleverse|Isaiah|66:17|9}} all denounce sacrifices made "in the gardens", which may also be connected to the cult of Tammuz.{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|Willem|1999|page=9}} Another possible allusion to Tammuz occurs in {{bibleverse|Daniel|11:37|9}}:{{sfn|Smith|2002|page=182}}{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|Willem|1999|page=9}}{{sfn|Middlemas|2005|page=115}} "Neither shall he regard the God of his fathers, nor the desire of women, nor regard any god: for he shall magnify himself above all." The subject of this passage is [[Antiochus IV Epiphanes]]{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|Willem|1999|page=9}} and some scholars have interpreted the reference to the "one desired by women" in this passage as an indication that Antiochus may have persecuted the cult of Tammuz.{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|Willem|1999|page=9}} There is no external evidence to support this reading, however,{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|Willem|1999|page=9}} and it is much more probable that this epithet is merely a jibe at Antiochus's notorious cruelty towards all the women who fell in love with him.{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|Willem|1999|page=9}}
The Hebrew Bible also contains references to Tammuz's consort Inanna-Ishtar.{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=193}} {{bibleverse|Jeremiah|7:18|9}} and {{bibleverse|Jeremiah|44:15–19|9}} mention "the Queen of Heaven", who is probably a syncretism of Inanna-Ishtar and the West Semitic goddess [[Astarte]].{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=193}}{{sfn|Breitenberger|2007|page=10}}{{sfn|Smith|2002|page=182}}{{sfn|Ackerman|2006|pages=116–117}} The [[Song of Songs]] bears strong similarities to the Sumerian love poems involving Inanna and Dumuzid,{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=194}} particularly in its usage of natural symbolism to represent the lovers' physicality.{{sfn|Pryke|2017|page=194}} {{bibleverse|Song of Songs|6:10|9}} ("Who is she that looketh forth as the morning, fair as the moon, clear as the sun, and terrible as an army with banners?") is almost certainly a reference to Inanna-Ishtar.{{sfn|Baring|Cashford|1991}}
===Classical antiquity=== [[File:Women Adonia Louvre CA1679.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Fragment of an Attic red-figure wedding vase ({{circa}} 430-420 BC), showing women climbing ladders up to the roofs of their houses carrying "gardens of Adonis"]]
The myth of [[Inanna]] and Dumuzid later became the basis for the Greek myth of [[Aphrodite]] and [[Adonis]].{{snf|West|1997|page=57}}{{snf|Kerényi|1951|page=67}}{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}} The [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] name {{lang|grc|Ἄδωνις}} (''Adōnis'', {{IPA-el|ádɔːnis}}) is derived from the [[Canaanite languages|Canaanite]] word ''ʼadōn'', meaning "lord".{{sfn|Burkert|1985|pages=176–177}}{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}} The earliest known Greek reference to Adonis comes from a fragment of a poem by the [[Lesbos|Lesbian]] poetess [[Sappho]], dating to the seventh century BC,{{sfn|West|1997|pages=530–531}} in which a chorus of young girls asks Aphrodite what they can do to mourn Adonis's death.{{sfn|West|1997|pages=530–531}} Aphrodite replies that they must beat their breasts and tear their tunics.{{sfn|West|1997|pages=530–531}} Later rescensions of the Adonis legend reveal that he was believed to have been slain by a wild boar during a hunting trip.{{sfn|Kerényi|1951|page=76}}{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=96}} According to [[Lucian]]'s ''[[De Dea Syria]]'',{{sfn|Kerényi|1951|page=279}} each year during the festival of Adonis, the Adonis River in [[Lebanon]] (now known as the [[Abraham River]]) ran red with blood.{{sfn|Kerényi|1951|page=76}}
In Greece, the myth of Adonis was associated with the festival of the [[Adonia]], which was celebrated by Greek women every year in midsummer.{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}}<ref>W. Atallah, ''Adonis dans la littérature et l'art grecs'', Paris, 1966.</ref> The festival, which was evidently already celebrated in Lesbos by Sappho's time,{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}} seems to have first become popular in Athens in the mid-fifth century BC.{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}} At the start of the festival, the women would plant a "garden of Adonis",{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}} a small garden planted inside a small basket or a shallow piece of broken pottery containing a variety of quick-growing plants, such as [[lettuce]] and [[fennel]], or even quick-sprouting grains such as [[wheat]] and [[barley]].{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}}{{sfn|Detienne|1977}} The women would then climb ladders to the roofs of their houses,{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}} where they would place the gardens out under the heat of the summer sun.{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}} The plants would sprout in the sunlight,{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=97}} but wither quickly in the heat.{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|pages=97–98}} Then the women would mourn and lament loudly over the death of Adonis,{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=98}} tearing their clothes and beating their breasts in a public display of grief.{{sfn|Cyrino|2010|page=98}} The third century BC poet [[Euphorion of Chalcis]] remarked in his ''[[Hyacinth (mythology)|Hyacinth]]'' that "Only [[Cocytus]] washed the wounds of Adonis".<ref>Remarked upon in passing by [[Photios I of Constantinople|Photius]], ''Biblioteca'' 190 ([http://www.tertullian.org/fathers/photius_copyright/photius_05bibliotheca.htm on-line translation]).</ref>
===Survival into the Christian Era=== [[File:BethlehemInsideCN.jpg|thumb|The [[Church of the Nativity]] in [[Bethlehem]]. According to [[Jerome]], the site had temporarily been "overshadowed by a grove of Tammuz".{{sfn|Taylor|1993|page=96}}]] Traditional Mesopotamian religion began to gradually decline between the third and fifth centuries AD as [[Assyrian people|ethnic Assyrians]] converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Parpola|2004|page=17}} Nonetheless, the cult of Ishtar and Tammuz managed to survive in parts of Upper Mesopotamia.{{sfn|Warner|2016|page=211}} The [[Church Fathers|Church Father]] [[Jerome]] records in a letter dated to the year 395 AD that "Bethlehem... belonging now to us... was overshadowed by a grove of Tammuz, that is to say, Adonis, and in the cave where once the infant Christ cried, the lover of Venus was lamented."{{sfn|Taylor|1993|page=96}} This same cave later became the site of the Church of the Nativity.{{sfn|Taylor|1993|page=96}} The church historian [[Eusebius]], however, does not mention pagans having ever worshipped in the cave,{{sfn|Taylor|1993|page=96}} nor do any other early Christian writers.{{sfn|Taylor|1993|page=96}} Peter Welten has argued that the cave was never dedicated to Tammuz{{sfn|Taylor|1993|page=96}} and that Jerome misinterpreted Christian mourning over the [[Massacre of the Innocents]] as a pagan ritual over Tammuz's death.{{sfn|Taylor|1993|page=96}} Joan E. Taylor has countered this contention by arguing that Jerome, as an educated man, could not have been so naïve as to mistake Christian mourning over the Massacre of the Innocents as a pagan ritual for Tammuz.{{sfn|Taylor|1993|pages=96–97}}
During the sixth century AD, some [[Early Christianity|early Christians]] in the Middle East borrowed elements from poems of Ishtar mourning over the death of Tammuz into their own retellings of the [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Virgin Mary]] mourning over the death of her son [[Jesus]].{{sfn|Warner|2016|pages=210–212}}{{sfn|Baring|Cashford|1991}} The Syrian writers [[Jacob of Serugh]] and [[Romanos the Melodist]] both wrote laments in which the Virgin Mary describes her compassion for her son at the foot of the cross in deeply personal terms closely resembling Ishtar's laments over the death of Tammuz.{{sfn|Warner|2016|page=212}}
[[File:Harran beehive houses (2).JPG|thumb|The cult of Tammuz was still thriving in the city of [[Harran]] in the tenth and eleventh centuries AD.{{sfn|Warner|2016|page=211}}<ref name=Fullerp200/>{{sfn|Parpola|2004|page=17}}]]
Tammuz is the month of July in [[Iraqi Arabic]] and [[Levantine Arabic]] (see [[Arabic names of calendar months]]), as well as in the [[Assyrian calendar]] and [[Jewish calendar]],{{sfn|Cragg|1991|page=260}} and references to Tammuz appear in [[Arabic literature]] from the 9th to 11th centuries AD.<ref name=Fullerp200>Fuller, 1864, pp. 200-201.</ref> In what purports to be a translation of an ancient Nabataean (here meaning Aramaean) text by [[Qūthāmā]] the Babylonian, [[Ibn Wahshiyya]] (c. 9th-10th century AD), adds information on his own efforts to ascertain the identity of Tammuz, and his discovery of the full details of the legend of Tammuz in another Nabataean book: "How he summoned the king to worship the seven (planets) and the twelve (signs) and how the king put him to death several times in a cruel manner Tammuz coming to life again after each time, until at last he died; and behold! it was identical to the legend of [[St. George]]."<ref name=Azevedop308>de Azevedo and Stoddart, 2005, pp. 308-309.</ref> Ibn Wahshiyya also adds that Tammuz lived in [[Babylonia]] before the coming of the [[Chaldea]]ns and belonged to an ancient [[Mesopotamia]]n tribe called Ganbân.<ref name=Fullerp200/> On rituals related to Tammuz in his time, he adds that the [[Sabaeans]] in [[Harran]] and Babylonia still lamented the loss of Tammuz every July, but that the origin of the worship had been lost.<ref name=Fullerp200/>
In the tenth century AD, the Arab traveler [[Ibn al-Nadim|Al-Nadim]] wrote in his ''Kitab al-Fehrest'' that "All the [[Sabaeans]] of our time, those of Babylonia as well as those of [[Harran]], lament and weep to this day over Tammuz at a festival which they, more particularly the women, hold in the month of the same name."{{sfn|Warner|2016|page=211}} Drawing from a work on [[Syriac Christianity|Syriac]] calendar feast days, Al-Nadim describes a Tâ'ûz festival that took place in the middle of the month of Tammuz.<ref name=Fullerp200/> Women bewailed the death of Tammuz at the hands of his master who was said to have "ground his bones in a mill and scattered them to the wind."<ref name=Fullerp200/> Consequently, women would forgo the eating of ground foods during the festival time.<ref name=Fullerp200/> The same festival is mentioned in the eleventh century by [[Ibn Athir]], who recounts that it still took place every year at the appointed time along the banks of the [[Tigris]] river.<ref name=Fullerp200/> The cult of Ishtar and Tammuz still existed in [[Mardin]] as late as the eighteenth century.{{sfn|Parpola|2004|page=17}} ''Tammuz'' is still the name for the month of July in [[Mesopotamian Arabic|Iraqi Arabic]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=73}}
==Dying-and-rising god archetype== [[File:JamesGeorgeFrazer.jpg|thumb|Photograph of [[James George Frazer|Sir James George Frazer]], the [[Anthropology|anthropologist]] who is most directly responsible for promoting the concept of a "dying and rising god" archetype{{sfn|Ehrman|2012|pages=222–223}}{{sfn|Barstad|1984|page=149}}{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=142–143}}]] {{main|Dying-and-rising deity}} The late nineteenth-century Scottish [[Anthropology|anthropologist]] [[James George Frazer|Sir James George Frazer]] wrote extensively about Tammuz in his monumental study of comparative religion ''[[The Golden Bough]]'' (the first edition of which was published in 1890){{sfn|Ehrman|2012|pages=222–223}}{{sfn|Mettinger|2004|page=375}} as well as in later works.{{sfn|Barstad|1984|pages=149–150}} Frazer claimed that Tammuz was just one example of the archetype of a "dying-and-rising god" found throughout all cultures.{{sfn|Barstad|1984|page=149}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2012|pages=222–223}}{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=140–142}} Frazer's main intention was to prove that all religions were fundamentally the same{{sfn|Ehrman|2012|page=222}} and that all the essential features of Christianity could be found in earlier religions.{{sfn|Barstad|1984|page=150}} Frazer's arguments were criticized as sloppy and amateurish from the beginning,{{sfn|Barstad|1984|page=149}} but his claims became widely influential in late nineteenth and early twentieth century scholarship of religion.{{sfn|Barstad|1984|page=149}}{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=142–143}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2012|pages=222–223}}
Tammuz's categorization as a "dying-and-rising god" was based on the abbreviated Akkadian redaction of ''Inanna's Descent into the Underworld'', which was missing the ending.{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=144}}{{sfn|Mettinger|2004|page=379}} Since numerous lamentations over the death of Dumuzid had already been translated, scholars filled in the missing ending by assuming that the reason for Ishtar's descent was because she was going to resurrect Dumuzid and that the text could therefore be assumed to end with Tammuz's resurrection.{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=144}} Then, in the middle of the twentieth century, the complete, unabridged, original Sumerian text of ''Inanna's Descent'' was finally translated,{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=144}}{{sfn|Mettinger|2004|page=379}} revealing that, instead of ending with Dumuzid's resurrection as had long been assumed, the text actually ended with Dumuzid's ''death''.{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=144}}{{sfn|Mettinger|2004|page=379}} The discovery of the ''Return of Dumuzid'' in 1963 briefly revived hopes that Dumuzid might once again be able to be categorized as a "dying-and-rising god",{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=144}} but the text ultimately proved disappointing in this regard because it does not describe a triumph over death (as would be necessary for a true Frazerian "resurrection myth"){{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=144}}{{sfn|Smith|1987|pages=521–527}} and instead does precisely the opposite and affirms the "inalterable power of the realm of the dead" by the fact that Dumuzid can only leave the Underworld when his sister takes his place.{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=144}}{{sfn|Smith|1987|pages=521–527}} Frazer and others also saw Tammuz's Greek equivalent Adonis as a "dying-and-rising god",{{sfn|Barstad|1984|page=149}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2012|pages=222–223}}{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=140–142}} despite the fact that he is never described as rising from the dead in any extant Graeco-Roman writings{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|page=143}} and the only possible allusions to his supposed resurrection come from late, highly ambiguous statements made by Christian authors.{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|page=143}}{{efn|[[Origen]] discusses Adonis, (whom he associates with Tammuz), in his ''Selecta in Ezechielem'' ( “Comments on Ezekiel”), noting that "they say that for a long time certain rites of initiation are conducted: first, that they weep for him, since he has died; second, that they rejoice for him because he has risen from the dead (''apo nekrôn anastanti'')" (cf. J.-P. Migne, ''Patrologiae Cursus Completus: Series Graeca'', '''13:800''').}}
Around the same time that the notion of Tammuz as a "dying-and-rising god" became discredited, scholars began to severely criticize the designation of "dying-and-rising god" altogether.{{sfn|Barstad|1984|pages=149–150}}{{sfn|Smith|1987|pages=521–527}}{{sfn|Mettinger|2004|page=374}} In 1987, [[Jonathan Z. Smith]] concluded in [[Mircea Eliade]]'s ''Encyclopedia of Religion'' that "The category of dying and rising gods, once a major topic of scholarly investigation, must now be understood to have been largely a misnomer based on imaginative reconstructions and exceedingly late or highly ambiguous texts."{{sfn|Smith|1987|pages=521–527}}{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|page=143}} He further argued that the deities previously referred to as "dying-and-rising" would be better termed separately as "dying gods" and "disappearing gods",{{sfn|Smith|1987|pages=521–527}}{{sfn|Mettinger|2004|page=374}} asserting that before Christianity, the two categories were distinct and gods who "died" did not return, and those who returned never truly "died".{{sfn|Smith|1987|pages=521–527}}{{sfn|Mettinger|2004|page=374}} By the end of the twentieth century, most scholars had come to agree that the notion of a "dying-and-rising god" was an invention{{sfn|Ehrman|2012|page=223}}{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=142–143}}{{sfn|Mettinger|2004|pages=374–375}} and that the term was not a useful scholarly designation.{{sfn|Ehrman|2012|page=223}}{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pages=142–143}}{{sfn|Mettinger|2004|pages=374–375}}
==Literary references== [[File:Paradise Lost 6.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Tammuz appears as one of [[Satan]]'s demons in Book I of [[John Milton]]'s ''[[Paradise Lost]]'',{{sfn|Milton|Kastan|2005|pages=25–26}} shown here in this engraving from 1866 by Gustave Doré]]
The references to the cult of Tammuz preserved in the Bible and in Greco-Roman literature brought the story to the attention of western European writers.{{sfn|Milton|Kastan|2005|page=25}} The story was popular in [[Early modern Britain|Early Modern England]] and appeared in a variety of works, including [[Walter Raleigh|Sir Walter Raleigh]]'s ''History of the World'' (1614), [[George Sandys]]'s ''Dictionarium Relation of a Journey''(1615), and Charles Stephanus's ''Dictionarium Historicam'' (1553).{{sfn|Milton|Kastan|2005|page=25}} These have all been suggested as sources for Tammuz's most famous appearance in English literature as a demon in Book I of [[John Milton]]'s ''[[Paradise Lost]]'', lines 446-457:{{sfn|Milton|Kastan|2005|pages=25–26}} <blockquote> THAMMUZ came next behind, <br> Whose annual wound in LEBANON allur'd <br> The SYRIAN Damsels to lament his fate <br> In amorous dittyes all a Summers day, <br> While smooth ADONIS from his native Rock <br> Ran purple to the Sea, suppos'd with blood <br> Of THAMMUZ yearly wounded: the Love-tale <br> Infected SION'S daughters with like heat, <br> Whose wanton passions in the sacred Porch <br> EZEKIEL saw, when by the Vision led <br> His eye survey'd the dark Idolatries <br> Of alienated JUDAH. </blockquote>
*[[Oscar Wilde]], "Charmides" <blockquote> And then each pigeon spread its milky van, <br> The bright car soared into the dawning sky <br> And like a cloud the aerial caravan <br> Passed over the Ægean silently, <br> Till the faint air was troubled with the song <br> From the wan mouths that call on bleeding Thammuz all night long </blockquote>
