{{Slavic Native Faith}}
'''[[Slavic Native Faith]]''' (Rodnovery) '''in [[Ukraine]]''' has an unspecified number of adherents which ranges between the thousands and the tens of thousands. A movement within Rodnovery which is unique to Ukraine is the [[Native Ukrainian National Faith]], established by Lev Sylenko in the 1960s among the [[Ukrainian diaspora]] in [[North America]], and introduced in Ukraine only in the 1990s.

==Demographics==
[[File:Ukraine RUNVira Sylenkoite temple worship (0).png|thumb|People gathered for worship at a Native Ukrainian National Faith's temple in Ukraine.]]
In 2005, Ivakhiv noted that there were likely between 5000 and 10,000 Rodnovers in Ukraine.{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005|p=224}} He also observed that it had undergone dramatic growth in the country since the early and mid 1990s.{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005|p=209}} Other sociologists estimated that in the same years Ukrainian Rodnovers were more than 90,000 (0.2% of the total population).<ref name=Ivakhiv2006>Ivakhiv, Adrian (2006). "Neo-Paganism in Ukraine". Taylor, Bron. ''The Encyclopedia of Religion and Nature'', [http://users.clas.ufl.edu/bron/ern/N.pdf Letter N]. Continuum. {{ISBN|9780199754670}}</ref>{{rp|1189}}

Ivakhiv noted that the average age of Ukrainian Rodovers was older than the average age of Pagans in the West,{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005|p=224}} and also noted that the religion's "main base" was "nationally oriented ethnic Ukrainians of higher-than-average educational levels".{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005|p=224}} He observed that there was overlap between the Rodnover communities and other sectors of Ukrainian society, such as the folk and traditional music revival groups, Cossack associations, traditional martial arts groups, and nationalist and ultra-nationalist organisations.{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005|p=234}} He added that Rodnovery remains "a relatively small niche in Ukrainian religious culture",{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005|p=231}} and that it faces a mixed reception in the country.{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005|pp=233–234}} Established Ukrainian Orthodox and Roman Catholic groups have viewed Slavic Native Faith with alarm and hostility,{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005|p=234}} while the country's educated and intellectual classes tend to view it as a fringe part of the ultra-conservative movement which was tinged with anti-Semitism and xenophobia.{{sfn|Ivakhiv|2005|p=234}}

In the global Ukrainian diaspora, there has been a "great decline" in the numbers practising the [[Native Ukrainian National Faith]] branch of Rodnovery.{{sfn|Lesiv|2017|p=136}} This has been due to the branch's inability to attract sufficient numbers of youth in this community.{{sfn|Lesiv|2017|p=148}} Alternately, the Ukrainian organisation Ancestral Fire of the Native Orthodox Faith has established groups in both Moldova and Germany.{{sfn|Lesiv|2017|p=140}} In Ukraine, much like in Russia, Rodnovery is very popular among Cossacks, and the variety that they embrace, [[Assianism]], is linked to a rediscovery of [[Scythians|Scythian]] identity. Pilkington and Popov report one Russian Cossack saying that in Ukraine it is easier to meet Rodnover Cossacks than Christian Cossacks.{{sfn|Pilkington|Popov|2009|pp=275–276}}

==Ukrainian and Russian Rodnovers' involvement in the War in Donbass==
Rodnovery has a significant role in the [[War in Donbass]], with many Rodnovers forming or joining armed forces. Some of them—for example those of the Svarozich Battalion—have been fighting in favour of Russia; other Rodnovers—such as those of the [[Azov Battalion]]—have taken the side of Ukraine.{{sfn|Skrylnikov|2016}} The war has stirred different reactions among Rodnovers in Ukraine; those belonging to the [[Native Ukrainian National Faith]] viewed Russia as the aggressor, while adherents of other Rodnover organisations like the Ancestral Fire of the Native Orthodox Faith more commonly saw Russians and Ukrainians as brothers and believed that the conflict was caused by the machinations of the United States.{{sfn|Lesiv|2017|pp=133–134, 140–141}}

Russian Rodnover military formations in [[Donbass]] include the Svarog, Varyag and Rusich formations, and Rodnovers within the [[Russian Orthodox Army]]. Observers have highlighted that Russian Rodnovers have been proselytising in the region, with the endorsement of Russia, under the name "Orthodoxy" and preaching the concept of a new "Russian World", and that their beliefs have even permeated the Orthodox Christian church.<ref>{{cite conference |last=Ageyev |first=Vyacheslav |title=Neo-paganism and Russian Orthodoxy – an explosive mix of religion and ideology |url=http://ahamot.org/en/neo-paganism-and-russian-orthodoxy-an-explosive-mix-of-religion-and-ideology/ |date=27 August 2015 |conference=XXI World Congress of the International Association for the History of Religions (IAHR), 23–29 August 2015 |location=Erfurt, Germany |conference-url=http://www.iahr2015.org/iahr/2249.html |accessdate=7 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707163055/http://ahamot.org/en/neo-paganism-and-russian-orthodoxy-an-explosive-mix-of-religion-and-ideology/ |archive-date=7 July 2017}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20170707162828/http://www.iahr2015.org/iahr/2249.html Archived pertinent panel of the XXI IAHR conference].</ref>

==Rodnover organisations in Ukraine==
As of 2016, the Ukrainian government granted official recognition only to four Rodnover organisations, among [[list of Slavic Native Faith's organisations#Ukaine|tens of them]], and to more than thirty other congregations not affiliated with the four. The four Rodnover organisations with official registration as religious entities are the following ones:<ref name=RISU2016>RISU (Religion Information Service of Ukraine): [https://risu.org.ua/ua/index/resourses/statistics/ukr2016/63055/ Релігійні організації в Україні (станом на 1 січня 2016 р.) — State-recognised religious organisations as of 2016].</ref>
* Ancestral Fire of the Native Orthodox Faith (Родового Вогнища Рідної Православної Віри);
* Churches of the Ukrainian Gentiles (Церкви Українських Язичників);
* Federation of Ukrainian Rodnovers (Объединение Родноверов Украины) led by Halyna Lozko (Volkhvynia Zoreslava);
* [[Native Ukrainian National Faith]]'s main body.

